  <h2>Types of Divorce in Maryland</h2>

  <h3>Uncontested Divorce</h3>
  <p>
    An uncontested divorce occurs when both spouses agree on all material issues — including property division, spousal support, child custody, and child support. Maryland law allows for an absolute divorce when spouses have lived apart for a required period or have reached a mutual agreement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Even in uncontested divorces, having an attorney review your separation agreement and divorce documents is essential. A poorly drafted agreement can have long-lasting consequences that aren't apparent until years later. Our attorneys ensure your agreement truly protects your interests.
  </p>

  <h3>Contested Divorce</h3>
  <p>
    A contested divorce arises when spouses cannot agree on one or more key issues. Contested matters may involve disagreements over:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Division of marital property and assets</li>
    <li>Spousal support (alimony)</li>
    <li>Child custody and visitation arrangements</li>
    <li>Child support amounts</li>
    <li>Debt allocation</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Contested divorces typically require court intervention and may involve discovery, depositions, expert witnesses, and hearings. Our attorneys are fully prepared to advocate for you at every stage of litigation.
  </p>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <h3 style="margin-top:0; color:#0D6E6E;">Maryland Divorce Grounds</h3>
    <p>Maryland recognizes <strong>no-fault divorce</strong> (based on a 12-month separation or mutual consent) and <strong>fault-based grounds</strong> including adultery, desertion, cruelty of treatment, and excessively vicious conduct. Our attorneys will advise you on which grounds are most appropriate and strategic for your situation.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The Maryland Divorce Process</h2>
  <p>Understanding what to expect can ease the stress of the divorce process. Here's a general overview:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Initial Consultation:</strong> Review your situation, goals, and legal options with one of our attorneys.</li>
    <li><strong>Filing the Complaint:</strong> We file your Complaint for Absolute Divorce in the appropriate Maryland Circuit Court.</li>
    <li><strong>Service of Process:</strong> Your spouse is formally served with the divorce papers.</li>
    <li><strong>Discovery:</strong> Exchange of financial information, assets, and other relevant documents.</li>
    <li><strong>Negotiation / Mediation:</strong> Attempt to resolve disputes outside of court when possible.</li>
    <li><strong>Trial or Settlement:</strong> If agreement cannot be reached, the case proceeds to trial.</li>
    <li><strong>Final Decree:</strong> The court issues an Absolute Divorce decree finalizing the divorce.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>What Happens to Property in a Maryland Divorce?</h2>
  <p>
    Maryland is an <strong>equitable distribution</strong> state, meaning marital property is divided fairly — though not necessarily equally — based on various factors including:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Length of the marriage</li>
    <li>Each spouse's monetary and non-monetary contributions</li>
    <li>Each spouse's economic circumstances</li>
    <li>How and when property was acquired</li>
    <li>Dissipation of marital assets</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="gold-box">
    <strong>Important:</strong> Not all property is subject to division. Separate property — assets owned before marriage or received as gifts or inheritance — is generally not subject to equitable distribution. However, commingling separate and marital funds can complicate this distinction. Our attorneys will carefully analyze your assets to protect what is rightfully yours.
  </div>

  <h2>Spousal Support in a Maryland Divorce</h2>
  <p>
    Maryland courts may award alimony (spousal support) in three forms: <strong>pendente lite</strong> (temporary support during the proceedings), <strong>rehabilitative alimony</strong> (time-limited support to help a spouse become self-supporting), and <strong>indefinite alimony</strong> (for cases of significant disparity in living standards or where rehabilitation is not practical).
  </p>

  <h2>Children and Divorce</h2>
  <p>
    When children are involved, the divorce also encompasses child custody and child support determinations. Maryland courts use the <strong>best interests of the child</strong> standard to determine appropriate custody arrangements. Our attorneys are particularly skilled in custody matters — it is the cornerstone of our practice.
  </p>

